    'tools.watertemp.meta.title': 'Water Temp Predictor | Barista Flow',
    'tools.watertemp.meta.desc': 'Use Newton\'s Law of Cooling to predict your kettle\'s temperature drop.',
    'tools.watertemp.h2': 'Why Predict Water Temperature?',
    'tools.watertemp.p1': 'Water temperature is critical for extraction. Boiling water can cause over-extraction and bitterness.',
    'tools.watertemp.p2': 'Using a thermometer every time disrupts workflow.',
    'tools.watertemp.p3': 'This tool uses physics to calculate the exact wait time for your water to naturally cool to the perfect target temperature.',
    'tools.watertemp.script.stainless': 'Stainless steel hand brew kettle',
    'tools.watertemp.script.impossible': 'Unable to achieve',
    'tools.bean.faq.1.q': 'What is the "degassing" process of coffee beans?',
    'tools.bean.faq.1.a': 'During the roasting process, coffee beans produce large amounts of carbon dioxide that is locked within the cell structure. Freshly roasted coffee beans outgas very violently. If brewed immediately, a large number of bubbles will prevent the contact between hot water and coffee powder, resulting in insufficient extraction and weak flavor. The so-called "bean raising" is the process of letting coffee beans stand for a few {t(\'tools.bean.status.days2\')} to allow excess carbon dioxide to be naturally released and achieve the best balance of coffee flavor.',
    'tools.bean.faq.2.q': 'How to properly store coffee beans to maintain freshness?',
    'tools.bean.faq.2.a': 'The three enemies of preserving coffee beans are: oxygen, light and moisture. The best way to store coffee beans is to place them in a sealed bag with a one-way exhaust valve or an opaque vacuum jar in a cool, dry cupboard without direct sunlight. Never place frequently used coffee beans in the refrigerator, because the moisture generated by the temperature difference when opening and closing the refrigerator will cause the coffee beans to quickly become damp and absorb odors.',
    'tools.bean.faq.3.a': 'Yes, but there are strict conditions. If you buy a large amount of coffee beans that you can\'t finish within a month, you can "portion" them into small single-brew portions (such as test tubes or vacuum bags) and place them deep in the freezer. When you want to brew, just take out the required amount "no need to remove the ice" and grind it immediately. Be careful not to repeatedly put the whole bag of beans in and out of the freezer, as this will completely destroy the flavor of the coffee.',
    'tools.bean.jsonld.name': 'Coffee beans and freshness calculator (Bean Freshness Calculator)',
    'tools.bean.jsonld.desc': 'Based on the roasting date and roasting degree of the coffee beans, it can accurately calculate whether it is in the golden flavor period and provide professional brewing parameter adjustment suggestions.',
    'tools.bean.meta.title': 'Coffee bean cultivation and freshness calculator | Golden flavor period prediction | Barista Flow',
    'tools.bean.meta.desc': 'Are your coffee beans growing well? Enter the roasting date, and our intelligent computer will tell you whether the coffee beans are currently in the exhaust period, golden flavor period or decline period, and give you the best brewing suggestions.',
    'tools.bean.title': 'Coffee beans and freshness calculator',
    'tools.bean.subtitle': 'Master the best extraction time. Enter the roasting date and roasting degree to understand the current flavor and off-gassing conditions of your coffee beans.',
    'tools.bean.label.date': '{t(\'tools.bean.setup.date\')} on wrapper',
    'tools.bean.label.level': 'Roast Level',
    'tools.bean.opt.light': 'Light Roast - Longer cultivation period',
    'tools.bean.opt.medium': 'Medium Roast - Standard',
    'tools.bean.opt.dark': 'Dark Roast - Drink as soon as possible',
    'tools.bean.status.passed': 'Baking day has passed',
    'tools.bean.status.days': 'sky',
    'tools.bean.status.current': 'Current flavor status',
    'tools.bean.status.golden': 'golden flavor period',
    'tools.bean.status.golden.desc': 'Exhaust has been completed and flavor development has reached its peak. Now is the most delicious moment for this bag of coffee beans.',
    'tools.bean.graph.title': 'Coffee bean life cycle curve',
    'tools.bean.graph.phase1': 'exhaust period',
    'tools.bean.graph.phase3': 'mature stable period',
    'tools.bean.graph.phase4': 'flavor decline period',
    'tools.bean.advice.title': 'Brewing strategy suggestions',
    'tools.bean.empty.prompt': 'Please select the roasting date on the package for calculation',
    'tools.bean.faq.title': 'Frequently asked questions about coffee beans',
    'tools.bean.faq.3.q': 'Can I freeze coffee beans in the refrigerator?',
    'tools.bean.faq.1.a_text': 'During the roasting process, coffee beans produce large amounts of carbon dioxide that is locked within the cell structure. Freshly roasted coffee beans are very outgassing. If brewed immediately, a large number of bubbles will prevent the contact between hot water and coffee powder, resulting in insufficient extraction and weak flavor (that is, the common water channel effect). The so-called "bean raising" is a physical process in which coffee beans are left to rest for several days to allow excess carbon dioxide to be naturally released and to achieve the best balance of coffee flavor.',

    'tools.default.bean.aeropress': 'Guatemala Huihuitnango',
    'tools.default.bean.coldbrew': 'Dark Roasted Chocolate Mixed Beans',
    'tools.default.bean.frenchpress': 'Colombia washed',
    'tools.default.bean.v60': 'Ethiopia Yirgacheffe',
    'tools.default.grind.aeropress': 'Medium to fine grinding (such as fine sand)',
    'tools.default.grind.coldbrew': 'Very coarse grind',
    'tools.default.grind.frenchpress': 'Coarsely ground (like kosher salt)',
    'tools.default.grind.v60': 'Medium to fine grinding (for manual grinding only)',
    'tools.v60.p3': 'Hario V60 is one of the most popular hand-brewed coffee appliances in the world. Its unique 60-degree tapered design, large-diameter bottom hole and spiral water guide give baristas a high degree of freedom in water flow control. But because of this, the V60 is very heavy on the rhythm and stability of water injection. This <strong>{t(\'tools.v60.title\')} (V60 Calculator)</strong> and timer are designed to solve this pain point.',
    'grind.meta.desc': 'Accurately convert the grinding scales of major brands of grinders (Comandante C40, Timemore, Fellow Ode, Baratza Encore, Kalita) to find the most perfect brewing parameters.',
    'grind.tooltip.turkish': 'Very fine (Türkiye)',
    'grind.tooltip.espresso': 'thin (Italian)',
    'grind.tooltip.aeropress': 'Medium fine (AeroPress/V60)',
    'grind.tooltip.frenchpress': 'medium coarse (press)',
    'grind.tooltip.coldbrew': 'Extremely thick (cold brew)',
    'grind.label.turkish': 'Türkiye',
    'grind.label.espresso': 'Espresso',
    'grind.label.v60': 'hand flush',
    'grind.label.frenchpress': 'French press',
    'grind.label.coldbrew': 'cold brew',
    'grind.h2_1': 'Why is grind scale conversion so important?',
    'grind.p1': 'In the world of specialty coffee, grind size is the most critical physical variable that determines extraction yield. Different grinders use completely different cutterhead geometries (Flat Burrs, Conical Burrs) and different fine-tuning pitches, which means that "Comandante C40\'s 20 grids" is definitely not equal to "Timemore C2\'s 20 grids."',
    'grind.h3_1': 'Universal Grind Ranges',
    'grind.p2': 'Our algorithm is not a simple linear multiplication, but a relative position (Percentage Interpolation) conversion based on the "sweet point interval" of each grinder under different brewing methods:',
    'grind.li1': '<strong>Extra Fine</strong>: As fine as flour. Specifically designed for Turkish coffee (Cezve/Ibrik).',
    'grind.li2': '<strong>Fine</strong>: The size of table salt. Suitable for espresso, it can provide great water resistance to build a pressure of 9 Bar.',
    'grind.li3': '<strong>Medium-Fine</strong>: Best for pour-over coffee (V60, Kalita Wave) and AeroPress. It extracts the perfect balance of sweet and sour in just 2-3 minutes.',
    'grind.li4': '<strong>Medium-Coarse</strong>: Like coarse sea salt. Suitable for French Press or Chemex to avoid bitterness caused by over-soaking.',
    'grind.li5': '<strong>Extra Coarse</strong>: Cold Brew suitable for long-term low-temperature steeping to minimize the extraction of impurities.',
    'grind.h3_2': 'Disclaimer and Tweaking Suggestions',
    'grind.p3': 'Please note that even the same model of grinder may vary due to <strong>the degree of wear of the cutterhead</strong>, the <strong>zero point setting</strong> and the <strong>roast degree of the coffee beans</strong>. The value provided by this converter is the starting point. <br/> We strongly recommend that if the brewed coffee feels too sour (under-extracted), please adjust the scale 1-2 steps finer; if the brewed coffee feels burnt or bitter or the water flow is stagnant (over-extraction), please adjust the scale 1-2 steps coarser.',
    'grind.script.turkish': 'Very fine (Turkish)',
    'grind.script.espresso': 'Fine powder (Espresso)',
    'grind.script.aeropress': 'Medium and fine (AeroPress)',
    'grind.script.v60': 'Medium (V60 manual)',
    'grind.script.frenchpress': 'medium coarse (French press)',
    'grind.script.coldbrew': 'Extremely thick (cold brew coffee)',

