    'glossary.meta.title': 'Coffee Glossary | Coffee Encyclopedia',
    'glossary.meta.desc': 'Encyclopedia of specialty coffee terminology. From steaming, channel effect to Menard reaction, we provide you with an in-depth analysis of the science and practical skills behind hand-brewed and espresso coffee.',
    'glossary.tag': 'Knowledge Base',
    'glossary.title': 'Coffee Encyclopedia',
    'glossary.subtitle': 'Only by mastering the terminology can you master the soul of brewing. This is an A-Z encyclopedia for coffee lovers, providing you with an in-depth analysis of the chemistry, physics and techniques behind every brew.',
    'glossary.readMore': 'Read full definition',
    'glossary.breadcrumb': 'Encyclopedia',
    'glossary.post.meta.suffix': '| Coffee Encyclopedia',

    'blog.meta.title': 'Coffee Knowledge Base | Barista Flow Professional Guide to Specialty Coffee Brewing',
    'blog.meta.desc': 'Here, we share with you the science of pour-over coffee, the physics of water temperature, the golden calibration of grind size, and brewing secrets from the world’s top baristas. Master the key variables and brew master-class specialty coffee at home.',
    'blog.tag': 'Coffee Academy',
    'blog.title': 'Coffee knowledge base',
    'blog.subtitle': 'Brewing coffee is a delicate art that combines physics and chemistry. Here, we decipher for you the scientific rules behind grinding degree, water temperature, and three-stage water injection method, and accompany you on your journey to become a barista.',
    'blog.readMore': 'Read more',
    'blog.breadcrumb': 'knowledge base',
    'blog.author': 'author:',
    'blog.cta.title': 'Like this article?',
    'blog.cta.desc': 'Use Barista Flow\'s professional timer to turn brewing science into the ultimate taste on your tongue in no time!',
    'blog.cta.btn': 'Start brew timer immediately',
    'blog.post.meta.suffix': '| Barista Flow Coffee Science',

    'tools.bean.jsonld.name': 'Coffee Bean Freshness Calculator',
    'tools.bean.jsonld.desc': 'Professional coffee bean exhaust and bean maintenance period computer. Predict the best flavor period based on the degree of roasting, avoid channeling effects caused by excessive carbon dioxide, and accurately grasp the golden extraction time.',
    'tools.bean.meta.title': 'Coffee bean cultivation period calculator | Best flavor period prediction | Barista Flow',
    'tools.bean.meta.desc': 'Professional coffee bean exhaust and bean maintenance period computer. Enter the roasting date and roasting degree to predict the carbon dioxide emission status and golden flavor period, and teach you how to adjust the brewing strategy based on freshness.',
    'tools.bean.title': 'Bean growing period computer',
    'tools.bean.subtitle': 'Coffee beans need a rest just like people! Enter the roasting date and roasting degree to calculate the exhaust state for you and accurately capture the golden flavor period.',
    'tools.bean.setup.title': 'Baking information settings',
    'tools.bean.setup.date': 'Roast Date',
    'tools.bean.setup.level': 'Roast Level',
    'tools.bean.setup.level.light': 'Light Roast - floral and fruity sour aroma',
    'tools.bean.setup.level.medium': 'Medium Roast - balance of sweet and sour',
    'tools.bean.setup.level.dark': 'Dark Roast - rich cocoa',
    'tools.bean.status.title': 'Freshness status analysis',
    'tools.bean.status.empty': 'Please enter baking information on the left',
    'tools.bean.status.empty.desc': 'After selecting the date and roasting degree, the system will automatically analyze the current exhaust status.',
    'tools.bean.status.days1': 'Baked',
    'tools.bean.status.days2': 'sky',
    'tools.bean.h2_1': 'Why is it necessary to “raise beans”?',
    'tools.bean.p1': 'Coffee beans produce large amounts of **carbon dioxide (CO₂)** during the roasting process. The cells of freshly roasted beans (commonly known as "fresh coffee beans") are filled with these gases. If you grind and add water immediately, a large amount of carbon dioxide will be released instantly, forming a thick layer of bubbles. This will not only push the water away, but also cause a "channeling effect (Channeling)", making your coffee taste watery, with a sharp sour taste and lack of sweetness.',
    'tools.bean.p2': 'The so-called "Degassing/Resting" period is the process of placing coffee beans in a package with a one-way exhaust valve to allow the excess gas to be naturally and slowly released.',
    'tools.bean.h2_2': 'How does roasting degree affect degassing time?',
    'tools.bean.p3': 'Different roasting levels will completely change the cell structure of the coffee beans, thereby affecting the speed of exhaust:',
    'tools.bean.li1': '**Dark Roast**: Roasted for a long time, the cell walls become very fragile and porous, and there is often oil on the surface. Gas escapes very easily. Dark roasted beans typically only take **3 to 5 days** to degas and have a shorter overall lifespan.',
    'tools.bean.li2': '**Medium Roast**: Moderate structure, usually takes **7 to 14 days** to achieve optimal sweet and sour balance.',
    'tools.bean.li3': '**Light Roast**: The roasting time is short, the beans are hard, and the cell structure is intact. The gas is tightly locked inside and exhausts extremely slowly. Lightly roasted beans usually need at least **14 to 21 days** to show their best floral and fruity aroma and sweetness, and have a very long lifespan. Sometimes the flavor is still at its peak after being stored for a month.',
    'tools.bean.h2_3': '3 Frequently Asked Questions about Coffee Bean Preservation',
    'tools.bean.h3_1': 'Is the oil on the surface of the coffee beans bad?',
    'tools.bean.p4': 'uncertain. Oil leakage (oil leakage) is a normal physical phenomenon of dark roasted coffee beans, because high-temperature roasting causes the cell walls to rupture and the internal lipids to escape to the surface.但如果是「浅焙或中焙」的豆子突然大量出油，那通常意味着保存环境温度过高，或是存放时间过久，豆子已经开始老化。',
    'tools.bean.h3_2': 'What\'s the best way to preserve it?',
    'tools.bean.p5': 'The three enemies of preserving coffee beans are: oxygen, light and moisture. The best way to store coffee beans is to place them in a sealed bag with a one-way exhaust valve or an opaque vacuum jar in a cool, dry cupboard without direct sunlight. Never put coffee beans that are used frequently in the refrigerator into the refrigerator, because the moisture generated by the temperature difference when opening and closing the refrigerator will cause the coffee beans to get damp quickly and absorb the odor in the refrigerator.',
    'tools.bean.h3_3': 'Can I freeze coffee beans in the refrigerator?',
    'tools.bean.p6': 'Yes, but there are strict conditions. If you buy a large amount of coffee beans that you can\'t finish in a month, you can "portion" them into small single-brew portions (such as centrifuge tubes or vacuum bags) and place them deep in the freezer. When you want to brew, just take out the required amount "no need to remove the ice" and grind it immediately. Be careful not to repeatedly put the entire bag of beans in and out of the freezer, as the condensed moisture will completely destroy the flavor of the entire bag of coffee.',
    'tools.bean.script.fresh.title': 'Too Fresh',
    'tools.bean.script.fresh.desc': 'Coffee beans have just been roasted and contain a lot of carbon dioxide gas in their cells. At this time, the exhaust is too violent and the flavor has not yet stabilized.',
    'tools.bean.script.fresh.advice': '⚠️ **Forced Brewing Strategy**: If you must brew now, be sure to extend the "Bloom Time" to 45 to 60 seconds to allow enough time for the gas to escape and avoid insufficient extraction caused by channeling effects.',
    'tools.bean.script.peak.title': 'Peak Flavor Window',
    'tools.bean.script.peak.desc': 'The exhaust has slowed down, and the sweet-sour balance and aromatic substance development of the coffee have reached their most perfect peak. Now is the most delicious moment for this bag of coffee beans.',
    'tools.bean.script.peak.advice': '✨ **Best Brewing Strategy**: Just use standard parameters for brewing. The water temperature and grinding degree can be adjusted according to your regular habits. Enjoy!',
    'tools.bean.script.mature.title': 'Mature stable phase (Matured)',
    'tools.bean.script.mature.desc': 'The coffee beans have been completely degassed, and while the liveliest aromas have subsided slightly, the sweetness has become very concentrated and full-bodied.',
    'tools.bean.script.mature.advice': '☕ **Stable Brewing Strategy**: Due to the reduced exhaust volume, the resistance of water flow through the powder bed will be reduced. It is recommended to "fine the grind by 1 to 2 steps" or slightly increase the water temperature by 1°C to maintain a sufficient extraction rate.',
    'tools.bean.script.stale.title': 'Fading / Stale',
    'tools.bean.script.stale.desc': 'A large amount of aromatic substances have volatilized, the surface oil may begin to oxidize, and the flavor becomes monotonous or even has a slight woody or oily smell.',
    'tools.bean.script.stale.advice': '🆘 **Rescue Brewing Strategy**: To squeeze out the remaining aromatics, turn up the water temperature significantly (e.g. 94-95°C) and use a finer grind. Or, use these beans to make "Cold Brew". Cold brew can effectively cover up the shortcomings of old beans.',

    'tools.frenchpress.meta.title': 'French Press Coffee Calculator & Timer | French Press Coffee Calculator & Timer Assistant',
    'tools.frenchpress.meta.desc': 'French Press coffee calculator and timer. Teach you how to use a 1:12 golden powder to water ratio and coarse grinding to easily brew mellow, oily classic French press coffee.',
    'tools.frenchpress.jsonld.desc': 'Accurate French Press coffee grounds and water ratio computer and timer. Master the richness ratio of 1:12 for perfect soaking and extraction.',
    'tools.frenchpress.title': 'French press computer',
    'tools.frenchpress.subtitle': 'The best full immersion brewing method for beginners! It has been preloaded for you with the 1:12 rich water-to-powder ratio and coarse grind settings for the French press, so you can start your mellow extraction immediately.',
    'tools.frenchpress.h2_1': 'How to use this French Press computer?',
    'tools.frenchpress.p1': 'The French Press is a long-established and extremely popular brewing tool. Unlike the V60\'s drip filter method, the French Press uses "full immersion" extraction. The coffee powder is completely soaked in hot water for a long time, which allows it to extract more coffee oil and body. This <strong> French Press Calculator </strong> will help you accurately control the powder to water ratio and soaking time.',
    'tools.frenchpress.p2': 'We have preloaded a pink to water ratio of <strong>1:12</strong> for you, which is the most classic rich ratio for French press pots. Because the French press does not use a paper filter, the coffee crema is retained, and using a ratio of 1:12 to 1:15 creates a very rich mouthfeel. Simply enter your coffee bean weight above and the computer will automatically calculate the total amount of water required.',
    'tools.frenchpress.h2_2': '3 Pro Tips for French Press',
    'tools.frenchpress.li1': '<strong> Use Coarse Grind </strong>: The metal filter of the French press has larger pores. If the grinding is too fine, the coffee powder will pass through the metal mesh and run into your cup, causing a cloudy taste. A coarse grind (the size of coarse sea salt) is key to a successful French press.',
    'tools.frenchpress.li2': '<strong> Breaking the Crust </strong>: Wait 4 minutes after filling with water, and the coffee powder will form a crust (Crust) on the surface. Use a spoon to gently stir it to break it, allowing most of the coffee powder to sink to the bottom, and then use a spoon to remove the remaining white foam and fine powder on the surface. This step is called the "James Hoffmann Technique" and will make your French press coffee incredibly clean.',
    'tools.frenchpress.li3': '<strong> Don’t press it all the way </strong>: Many people are used to pressing the lever all the way to squeeze out the coffee powder. This will squeeze out the bitter substances and fine powder. You only need to gently press the pressure rod down to the position where it just touches the surface of the coffee powder for filtering.',
    'tools.frenchpress.h2_3': 'Common Mistakes',
    'tools.frenchpress.h3_1': '1. Soaking time is too short or too long',
    'tools.frenchpress.p3': 'Many people only soak for 2 minutes and rush to press down, which will lead to insufficient extraction and a sour and watery taste. Standard French press soaking time is <strong> 4 minutes </strong> . If you used the shell-breaking technique above, you can even let it sit for 5-8 minutes to allow the fine powder to completely settle.',
    'tools.frenchpress.h3_2': '2. Pour every last drop into the cup',
    'tools.frenchpress.p4': 'Even if the metal filter can block most of the coffee grounds, there will still be a lot of sludge at the bottom of the pot. When pouring coffee, please pour it slowly, and <strong>don\'t pour out the last sip of coffee</strong>, leave it at the bottom of the pot, and the coffee in your cup will be much cleaner.',
    'tools.frenchpress.h3_3': '3. Forgot to preheat the kettle body',
    'tools.frenchpress.p5': 'French presses are usually made of glass, and glass has a strong ability to absorb heat. If you pour 90°C hot water directly into a cold glass jug, the water temperature may instantly drop below 80°C, resulting in under-extraction. Be sure to warm the kettle with hot water before adding ground coffee.',
    'tools.frenchpress.p6': 'Are you ready? Use the timer above to set the 4-minute countdown and enjoy the mellow fat and original flavor brought by the French Press!',

    'grind.meta.title': 'Universal Grind Converter | Grinder Scale Comparison Chart | Barista Flow',
    'grind.meta.desc': 'Accurately convert the grinding scales of major brands of grinders (Comandante C40, Timemore C2/C3, Fellow Ode, Baratza Encore, etc.). Built-in perfect parameter comparison for Italian, manual and French press pots.',
    'grind.title': 'Universal Grind Converter',
    'grind.subtitle': 'I got a new grinder, but I don’t know what scale to use for the previous recipe? Through our algorithm, we can automatically help you perfectly map the original grinding scale to your new grinder.',
    'grind.source.title': 'Your current grinder',
    'grind.selectBrand': 'Select brand and model',
    'grind.currentScale': 'Current scale',
    'grind.target.title': 'Conversion target grinder',
    'grind.selectTarget': 'Select target brand and model',
    'grind.result': 'Conversion result',
    'grind.gauge.title': 'Brewing interval drop point',
    'grind.gauge.select': 'Please select scale',
    'grind.apply': 'Apply this scale to my timers',

    'terms.meta.title': 'Terms of Service | Barista Flow',
    'terms.meta.desc': 'Barista Flow Terms of Service and Disclaimer.',
    'terms.title': 'Terms of Service',
    'terms.date': 'Last updated: May 28, 2026',
    'terms.p1': 'Welcome to Barista Flow. Please read the following terms carefully before using this website. By using this website you agree to be bound by these terms.',
    'terms.s1.title': '1. Service Description',
    'terms.s1.p1': 'Barista Flow provides free online coffee brewing timers, recipe calculation tools and related coffee knowledge. This website is a static client application.',
    'terms.s2.title': '2. User Responsibilities',
    'terms.s2.p1': 'You agree not to use this website to conduct any illegal activities or disrupt the normal operation of the website. Any results generated by your use of this website (such as brewing recipes) are for informational purposes only.',
    'terms.s3.title': '3. Disclaimer',
    'terms.s3.p1': 'This website is provided "as is" without warranty of any kind. We do not guarantee that the website will always be error-free or uninterrupted. Due to different grinder models, cutterhead wear and coffee bean conditions, any brewing parameters and grinding degree conversion results provided on this website are only <strong>reference benchmarks</strong>, and we are not responsible for the flavor of the coffee you actually brew.',
    'terms.s4.title': '4. Intellectual property rights',
    'terms.s4.p1': 'The design, code, logo and text content of this website are protected by copyright law. No unauthorized copying or commercial use is allowed.',
    'terms.s5.title': '5. Third-party advertising and links',
    'terms.s5.p1': 'This website may contain Google AdSense ads and links to third-party websites. We are not responsible for the content of these advertisements and websites. Please see our Privacy Policy for more information.',
    'terms.s6.title': '6. Modification of terms',
    'terms.s6.p1': 'We reserve the right to modify these Terms at any time. The revised terms will be effective immediately after being posted on this page.',

    'privacy.meta.title': 'Privacy Policy Privacy Policy | Barista Flow',
    'privacy.meta.desc': 'Barista Flow\'s Privacy Policy and Cookie Statement, compliant with GDPR, CCPA and Google AdSense.',
    'privacy.title': 'Privacy Policy',
    'privacy.date': 'Last updated: May 28, 2026',
    'privacy.p1': 'Welcome to Barista Flow (the “Site”). We take your privacy very seriously. This privacy policy aims to explain how we collect, use and protect your personal data, and how this website uses cookies and third-party advertising services (especially Google AdSense).',
    'privacy.s1.title': '1. Data collection and use',
    'privacy.s1.p1': 'As a static client tool, this website <strong> will not actively ask you to register an account, nor will it send any of your coffee brewing recipes to our server </strong> . All brewing parameters and history records you enter are only stored in your local browser\'s <code> localStorage </code>.',
    'privacy.s2.title': '2. Cookies and Third-Party Tracking Technologies',
    'privacy.s2.p1': 'In order to provide the best browsing experience and maintain website operations, this website uses cookies and similar tracking technologies. When you browse this website, we or our third-party partners may store cookies on your device.',
    'privacy.s2.sub': 'Google AdSense and Advertising Cookies',
    'privacy.s2.p2': 'This website uses Google AdSense to serve third-party advertising. In order to comply with Google\'s publisher policies, we hereby declare:',
    'privacy.s2.l1': 'Third-party vendors, including Google, use cookies to serve ads. These ads are based on your previous visits to this and other websites.',
    'privacy.s2.l2': 'Google\'s use of <strong>advertising cookies</strong> allows Google and its partners to show you the most relevant ads based on your visit to our site and/or other sites on the Internet.',
    'privacy.s2.l3': 'You can opt out of personalized ads at any time by going to Google Ads Settings .',
    'privacy.s3.title': '3. GDPR and CCPA User Rights Statement',
    'privacy.s3.p1': 'We are committed to complying with the European General Data Protection Rule (GDPR) and the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA):',
    'privacy.s3.l1': '<strong> Consent and Withdrawal (GDPR) </strong> : We have a Cookie Consent banner at the bottom of our website. If you do not click consent, we will limit non-essential third-party tracking. You can reset your consent status at any time by clearing your browser cookies.',
    'privacy.s3.l2': '<strong> Do Not Sell Personal Information (CCPA) </strong>: This website will never collect or sell any of your personally identifiable information (PII). All advertising data delivery is handled anonymously by Google AdSense.',
    'privacy.s4.title': '4. External links',
    'privacy.s4.p1': 'Content or articles on this website may contain links to other external websites. Please note that we are not responsible for the privacy practices or content of these external sites. When you leave our website, we recommend that you read that website\'s privacy statement.',
    'privacy.s5.title': '5. Modifications to the policy',
    'privacy.s5.p1': 'We reserve the right to modify this privacy policy at any time. Any changes will be posted on this page and the "Last updated" date at the top will be updated. We encourage you to check this page regularly for the latest information.',
    'privacy.s6.title': '6. Contact us',
    'privacy.s6.p1': 'If you have any questions about this Privacy Policy or our data handling practices, please contact us through the Contact Us page.',

    'faq.meta.title': 'Frequently Asked Questions FAQ | Coffee Brewing Troubleshooting',
    'faq.meta.desc': 'Why is coffee bitter? How to calculate the pink to water ratio? Find the most expert pour-over coffee FAQs here and learn how to improve your brewing techniques.',
    'faq.title': 'Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)',
    'faq.subtitle': 'Frequently asked questions about hand-brewed coffee and timers',
    'faq.q1': 'Why does my hand-brewed coffee taste bitter?',
    'faq.a1': 'Bitterness in coffee is usually caused by "over-extraction." This may be caused by the water temperature being too high, the grind scale being too fine resulting in too much fine powder, or the extraction time being too long. It is recommended that you try to adjust the grinding degree by one or two notches, or use our professional brewing timer to accurately control the water injection time of each stage to avoid the dissolution of burnt and bitter substances in the later stage.',
    'faq.q2': 'How should coffee beans be stored to keep them fresh?',
    'faq.a2': 'The biggest enemies of coffee beans are oxygen, light, moisture and high temperature. The ideal way to store coffee beans is to place them in an opaque sealed jar or airtight bag with a one-way exhaust valve and place it in a cool, dry cupboard. Do not put coffee beans for daily use in the refrigerator to prevent condensation caused by temperature differences and accelerate the deterioration of the coffee beans.',
    'faq.q3': 'What is the difference in brewing between light roast and dark roast coffee?',
    'faq.a3': 'Lightly roasted coffee beans have a harder texture and a more floral and fruity flavor, requiring higher water temperatures (approximately 91°C-94°C) and finer grinding for full extraction; dark-roasted coffee beans have a looser structure, deep caramelization, and easy release of bitterness, so it is recommended to use lower water temperatures (approximately 85°C-88°C) and coarser grinding. If you\'re not sure how to adjust, try our brew recipe calculator to create parameters tailored to different roast levels.',
    'faq.q4': 'What is "Channeling" and how to avoid it?',
    'faq.a4': 'The channel effect means that water flows out in the powder bed through the shortcut with the least resistance, causing some powder to be over-extracted and some not to be extracted, resulting in coffee that is sour and bitter at the same time. To avoid channeling, make sure the powder is evenly distributed, use a better-quality grinder to reduce fines, and keep the water flow steady and gentle when filling with water, without vigorously washing the powder bed.',
    'faq.q5': 'How to grasp the Brew Ratio?',
    'faq.a5': 'The standard ground-to-water ratio for specialty hand-brewed coffee usually falls between 1:15 and 1:17 (i.e. 1 gram of ground coffee corresponds to 15 to 17 grams of water). 1:15 has a rich and mellow taste, while 1:17 is refreshing and bright. You can fine-tune it to your personal taste. With our Coffee Proportion Assistant, just enter the grams of coffee beans you have on hand and the system will automatically calculate the perfect amount of water for you.',
    'faq.q6': 'Why doesn’t the coffee powder expand during blooming?',
    'faq.a6': 'The bed of coffee grounds expands during steaming because the beans release the carbon dioxide produced during roasting. If there is no expansion at all, the most common reason is that the coffee beans have been left for too long and have exhausted their exhaust (no longer fresh); in addition, if it is extremely light roasted coffee, the exhaust reaction will be relatively weak. Just make sure the beans are consumed within a month of roasting and they will usually retain good flavor.',

    'privacy.meta.title': 'Privacy Policy Privacy Policy | Barista Flow',
    'privacy.meta.desc': 'Barista Flow\'s Privacy Policy and Cookie Statement, compliant with GDPR, CCPA and Google AdSense.',
    'privacy.title': 'Privacy Policy',
    'privacy.date': 'Last updated: May 28, 2026',
    'privacy.p1': 'Welcome to Barista Flow (the “Site”). We take your privacy very seriously. This privacy policy aims to explain how we collect, use and protect your personal data, and how this website uses cookies and third-party advertising services (especially Google AdSense).',
    'privacy.s1.title': '1. Data collection and use',
    'privacy.s1.p1': 'As a static client tool, this website <strong> will not actively ask you to register an account, nor will it send any of your coffee brewing recipes to our server </strong> . All brewing parameters and history records you enter are only stored in your local browser\'s <code> localStorage </code>.',
    'privacy.s2.title': '2. Cookies and Third-Party Tracking Technologies',
    'privacy.s2.p1': 'In order to provide the best browsing experience and maintain website operations, this website uses cookies and similar tracking technologies. When you browse this website, we or our third-party partners may store cookies on your device.',
    'privacy.s2.sub': 'Google AdSense and Advertising Cookies',
    'privacy.s2.p2': 'This website uses Google AdSense to serve third-party advertising. In order to comply with Google\'s publisher policies, we hereby declare:',
    'privacy.s2.l1': 'Third-party vendors, including Google, use cookies to serve ads. These ads are based on your previous visits to this and other websites.',
    'privacy.s2.l2': 'Google\'s use of <strong>advertising cookies</strong> allows Google and its partners to show you the most relevant ads based on your visit to our site and/or other sites on the Internet.',
    'privacy.s2.l3': 'You can opt out of personalized ads at any time by going to Google Ads Settings .',
    'privacy.s3.title': '3. GDPR and CCPA User Rights Statement',
    'privacy.s3.p1': 'We are committed to complying with the European General Data Protection Rule (GDPR) and the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA):',
    'privacy.s3.l1': '<strong> Consent and Withdrawal (GDPR) </strong> : We have a Cookie Consent banner at the bottom of our website. If you do not click consent, we will limit non-essential third-party tracking. You can reset your consent status at any time by clearing your browser cookies.',
    'privacy.s3.l2': '<strong> Do Not Sell Personal Information (CCPA) </strong>: This website will never collect or sell any of your personally identifiable information (PII). All advertising data delivery is handled anonymously by Google AdSense.',
    'privacy.s4.title': '4. External links',
    'privacy.s4.p1': 'Content or articles on this website may contain links to other external websites. Please note that we are not responsible for the privacy practices or content of these external sites. When you leave our website, we recommend that you read that website\'s privacy statement.',
    'privacy.s5.title': '5. Modifications to the policy',
    'privacy.s5.p1': 'We reserve the right to modify this privacy policy at any time. Any changes will be posted on this page and the "Last updated" date at the top will be updated. We encourage you to check this page regularly for the latest information.',
    'privacy.s6.title': '6. Contact us',
